THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"obtainableFactor","op":"set","value":0.008,"note":"Year-1 orderable flow limited to replacement, change orders, and un-spec'd white-space — below the modeled 1–5% band for reasons the band does not contemplate"}], likelihood 0.5, category model-structure

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "83% pre-let pipeline means the Year-1 PDU bill-of-materials is already written by someone else",
 "narrative": "The 3% obtainable factor treats SAM as an open order book. But FLAP-D vacancy is at a record-low 6.3% with the development pipeline 83% pre-let — and in pre-let builds, the electrical BOM including rack PDUs is specified at design/tender, 12–24 months before commissioning, almost always against incumbent framework agreements. A pre-launch entrant's first 12 months therefore address not 'the market' but the thin residue of break-fix replacement, late-stage change orders, and un-spec'd white-space — a flow that supports well under 1% of SAM, consistent with the hardware-entrant analogues (0.1%–0.001%) the corpus surfaced and the model's own crossCheck flagged before settling on 3%.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "FLAP-D vacancy hits a record low of 6.3% and the construction pipeline is 83% pre-let — capacity being delivered in 2026 already has committed tenants and, with them, committed electrical vendor stacks",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-DE#c21",
    "digest:geo-DE#c20"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The venture is pre-launch, targeting large operators first; those operators procure rack power against multi-year frameworks with the incumbent top-3 (CR3 ~0.55), so 2026–27 fit-out deliveries are contractually spoken for before the venture can even bid",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Stage",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "ledger:shape.cr3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "obtainableFactor's 3% mid-band is anchored to generic SOM benchmarks, not to the share of the flow that is actually orderable in the window; the pre-let lockout compresses reachable Year-1 demand to replacement and spot buys, well below the band's low end",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "3% looks humble — it sits in the middle of every published Year-1 SOM benchmark, so it reads as conservative. The surface appearance of 'we only need a tiny sliver' hides that share of a market is not share of the orderable flow: when 83% of near-term capacity is pre-let, most of the sliver was awarded before launch day.",
 "falsifier": "Two or more CE data-center fit-out tenders with 2026 delivery dates where the rack-PDU line item is still open to new vendors at time of bid (i.e., not pre-committed under a framework), and the venture is admitted to bid.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "The 83% pre-let figure and framework-based procurement in large-operator channels are documented; the counterweight is that replacement/retrofit demand in the 56% non-hyperscale base is genuinely spot-purchased, so full lockout is unlikely but material compression is probable. [evidence revision: The 83% pre-let / 6.3% vacancy figures and the pre-commitment-as-primary-route dynamic are now firmly documented by the primary source (JLL) and independent corroborators, strengthening the trigger and propagation steps. The unresolved element remains the magnitude of compression to obtainableFactor — pre-let capacity locks in the fit-out BOM but does not eliminate spot/replacement demand in the installed base, and no direct evidence quantifies the Year-1 orderable residue. Modest upward revision from 0.45 to 0.50 reflects strong confirmation of premises while retaining uncertainty on the model-impact magnitude.]"
}

Emit JSON: { title, narrative, mechanism: [{step, text, refs}], whyMissable, falsifier, likelihoodRationale }
